{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17487329","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17487329"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:06:14+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:06:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"321"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"321","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/321"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.13,0.74,0.01,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"321"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55060"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"321","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/321"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"321"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40578"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"33"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"104"},{"type":"tags","id":"128"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"1674"},{"type":"tags","id":"2602"},{"type":"tags","id":"2706"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4608"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"6509"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12912"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12400"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39719"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42057"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44892"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55060","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/55060"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 64-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a two-day history of progressively worsening shortness of breath and chest discomfort. She has a medical history of hypertension and type 2 diabetes mellitus. Her medications include metformin and amlodipine. She also reports having a viral illness with fever and cough that started a week ago.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears uncomfortable with pulse rate 116/min, blood pressure 92/64 mmHg, respiratory rate 26/min, oxygen saturation 94% on room air, and temperature 37.8\u00b0C. Her jugular venous pressure is elevated at 7 cm above the sternal angle and appears prominent. Heart sounds are muffled and difficult to auscultate due to rapid rate. Chest auscultation is clear. There is no peripheral oedema.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following investigations is most likely to determine the diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Chest X-ray","Electrocardiogram","Echocardiogram","Troponin level","D-dimer"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation strongly suggests viral-related pericarditis, complicated by cardiac tamponade. The patient exhibits all components of Beck\u0027s triad: hypotension, muffled heart sounds, and elevated jugular venous pressure (JVP). Additionally, she has tachycardia and dyspnoea, which are common in tamponade. Given this presentation, the most important next investigation is an \u003Cstrong\u003Eechocardiogram\u003C/strong\u003E. This non-invasive test can quickly confirm the diagnosis by demonstrating pericardial effusion, right ventricular diastolic collapse, and other signs of tamponade physiology. It is the gold standard for diagnosing cardiac tamponade and can guide management decisions, including pericardiocentesis if needed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile a \u003Cstrong\u003Echest X-ray\u003C/strong\u003E might show an enlarged cardiac silhouette in cardiac tamponade, it is less sensitive and specific than echocardiography. It would not provide the detailed information needed to confirm the diagnosis or guide immediate management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eelectrocardiogram\u003C/strong\u003E may show non-specific changes such as electrical alternans or low voltage QRS complexes in cardiac tamponade, but these findings are neither sensitive nor specific. It would not provide the definitive diagnosis that an echocardiogram can offer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Etroponin level\u003C/strong\u003E is useful for diagnosing myocardial infarction but would not be the most important test in this scenario where cardiac tamponade is suspected. While myocardial ischemia can occur in severe tamponade, confirming the tamponade itself is the priority.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003ED-dimer\u003C/strong\u003E test is primarily used to help rule out pulmonary embolism. While pulmonary embolism can present with similar symptoms, the clinical picture here (especially the prominent neck veins and muffled heart sounds) is more suggestive of cardiac tamponade. Therefore, echocardiography would be more appropriate as the next investigation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn summary, while all of these tests may have a role in the overall workup, an echocardiogram is the most important next investigation when cardiac tamponade is suspected, as it can provide rapid, definitive diagnosis and guide immediate management.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cardiac tamponade can present with dyspnoea, tachycardia, hypotension, and elevated JVP, which may mimic other cardiopulmonary conditions.","Echocardiography is the most important investigation for diagnosing cardiac tamponade.","Beck\u0027s triad (hypotension, muffled heart sounds, and elevated JVP) is characteristic of cardiac tamponade."],"references":["Appleton C, Gillam L, Koulogiannis K. Cardiac Tamponade. Cardiol Clin 2017; 35:525-37. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/29025544/","Jensen J, Poulsen S, Molgaard H. Cardiac tamponade: a clinical challenge. European Society of Cardiology. 2017:15;17-27 Available at:\u00a0https://www.escardio.org/Journals/E-Journal-of-Cardiology-Practice/Volume-15/Cardiac-tamponade-a-clinical-challenge","Sharma R Rezaee A.\u00a0Beck triad. In: Radiopaedia [online]. 2020. Available at: https://radiopaedia.org/articles/beck-triad"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40578"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"321"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40578","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/40578"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-13T09:41:34+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-13T09:42:14+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"321"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55060"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"33","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/33"},"attributes":{"emoji":"